==English==

===Etymology===
From [[Cockney rhyming slang]] ''to take the Mickey Bliss'' (for '''[[take the piss]]''') <!--Source http://www.peevish.co.uk/slang/t.htm#take_the_mickey -->

Micturations: Swear-words that do not pertain to body parts invariably refer to bodily functions or secretions. If you were to ridicule someone for being too 'full of themself', you would 'take the piss' out of them. As the word 'piss' became categorised as vulgar, the phrase was modified - 'taking the micturations', later shortened to 'taking the mickey' (nothing to do with a person called Michael).
http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A753527

===Intransitive verb phrase===
'''[[take]] the [[mickey]]''' ('''takes the mickey''', '''taking the mickey''', '''took the mickey''', '''taken the mickey''') 

===Alternative forms===
*'''take the Michael'''
*'''take the mick'''

#(''British slang'') To [[ridicule]] or [[mock]].
#:''Are you '''takin' the mickey'''? You'll get yer 'ead bashed in.''

